Egypt â€™s benchmark  EGX 30 Index (EGX30) 
declined the most since April 27, dropping 0.3 percent to
5,039.41 at the 2:30 p.m. close in Cairo today.  The following stocks rose or fell in Cairo. Symbols are in
parentheses.  Beltone Financial Holding (BTFH)   increased the most
since April 28, gaining 3.5 percent to 15.49 Egyptian pounds.
Shareholders of the Cairo-based investment bank delegated the
board to buy back shares in the next financial year, according
to a regulatory filing today.  GB Auto (AUTO EY) gained as much as 7.6 percent to 31
pounds. The shares closed 0.6 percent higher at 28.98 pounds.
The biggest independent carmaker in the Middle East bought back
323,940 shares from March 23 to April 22 out of the 6.4 million
shares it had planned to purchase.  Palm Hills Developments SAE (PHDC)   retreated the most in
a week, declining 3.1 percent to 1.89 pounds. The real-estate
developer received a notification that authorities in the
northwestern province of Matrouh canceled contracts for the sale
of 2,229 feddans (2,313 acres) to the company.  To contact the reporter on this story:
